The paper presents a new deep multi-task representation learning framework that learns cross-task sharing structure at every layer in a deep network. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) category. Additionally, the paper deals with deep learning and tensor factorization, which are also relevant to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) category. The paper also mentions experiments related to computer vision (cs.CV) and natural language processing (cs.CL), indicating that it may belong to these categories as well. Finally, the paper deals with neural networks, which is a topic relevant to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) category.
